Analysis.name: Providers' ease of placement
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: Low risk

Randomization scheme was computer-generated using randomization tables. Allocation sequence was concealed. The statistician conducting the randomization placed the allocation data in serially numbered closed opaque envelopes. A pharmacist was responsible for packaging the study and placebo medications. Study groups comparable related to baseline characteristics.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: Low risk

Participants and providers were blinded to group allocation (double-blinded). Placebo tablets were created by a pharmacist in the Department of Pharmaceuticals, Faculty of Pharmacy, to be identical in size, shape, weight, and color to the misoprostol tablets. Intention-to-treat analyses were performed.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: Outcome data were available for all participants randomized.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo: Method of measuring the outcome was appropriate. Measurement of the outcome was the same for both intervention groups. Outcome assessors were not aware of the intervention received by study participants.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: Low risk

Results presented align with the outcomes described in the published protocol. Provider ease of placement was assessed only using a 10 cm VAS versus assessment using multiple tools with selective reporting of results.
Overall.bias.support: See support for judgement statements by domain.
